  "prompt": "How do flu vaccines work?",
  "response": "Flu vaccines work by stimulating the body's immune system to develop antibodies against specific influenza viruses. Here's a breakdown of how they work:\n\n1. Composition:\n- Contain weakened or inactivated flu virus strains\n- Typically include multiple virus strains predicted to be most common that season\n\n2. Immune response:\n- When injected, the vaccine triggers the immune system to produce antibodies\n- Antibodies are proteins that help recognize and fight specific viruses\n- This process takes about two weeks to develop full protection\n\n3. Types of vaccines:\n- Inactivated vaccines (killed virus)\n- Live attenuated vaccines (weakened virus)\n- Recombinant vaccines (created using genetic engineering)\n\n4. Protection mechanisms:\n- Antibodies help identify and neutralize flu viruses\n- Prevent viruses from entering and infecting healthy cells\n- Reduce severity of infection if exposed to actual flu virus\n\n5. Annual updates:\n- Vaccine composition changes yearly\n- Based on predictions of which flu strains will be most prevalent\n- Helps maintain effectiveness against evolving viruses\n\nThe vaccine doesn't guarantee 100% protection but significantly reduces the risk of getting flu and minimizes potential complications.",
